        \begin {tikzcd}
            {F(x)} && {F(y)} \\
            \\
            {G(x)} && {G(y)}
            \arrow ["{F(f)}", from=1-1, to=1-3]
            \arrow ["{G(f)}", from=3-1, to=3-3]
            \arrow ["{\alpha _x}", from=1-1, to=3-1]
            \arrow ["{\alpha _y}", from=1-3, to=3-3]
        \end {tikzcd}

Given any category \mathcal {C}, and any set \{X_i\}_{i\in  I} of
    its objects, the product of all these objects is, if it exists, an object
             \prod _{i\in  I} X_i \in  \mathcal {C}     
    equipped with morphisms (projections)
             p_i : \left (\prod _{i\in  I} X_i\right ) \to  X_i     
    for each i\in  I, such that it is universal with this property, i.e.
    such that given any other object Q\in  C with morphisms
             Q \xrightarrow {f_i} X_i      
    there is a unique morphism
             (f_i)_{i\in  I} : Q \to  \prod _{i\in  I} X_i     
    where the following diagram commutes:





